Rafe and Matthis stood with arms folded before the gallows. Droplets on the top beam sparkled in the sun. The gibbets hung from it in shadow. Bones clacked on chains in the wind. The dead wizard made no sound. It had sunk to its ankles in the mud. Its sockets did not leave the gibbets.

"They called me an incubus," Matthis said. "They asked me not to ... to dominate them."

Rafe nodded and said nothing. Matthis shivered, but not with cold.

"How long have you known," said Matthis, his eyes on the skeletons, "that you're an incubus?"

Rafe took a long breath. "You're stalling, Matthis."

Matthis looked sideways at Rafe. His lips had thinned, and his eyes were hard.

Matthis looked at his boots and shifted his weight between them. "I don't want it to hurt again," he whispered.

Rafe placed a hand on Matthis' shoulder, his eyes forward. Matthis breathed until his ribs stopped shaking. He stepped forward.

The skeleton on the far right of the gallows strained in his gibbet toward Matthis, who seized both of its pale wrists before the bony fingers could rip his eyes out. The jaws opened and shut with a hollow gock, gock, gock. Matthis closed his eyes and focused as Rafe had taught him earlier.

Magic felt like rage. It pulsed in his veins. Every muscle screamed with it. A surge built in his chest and stomach. Matthis flexed every muscle in his body and pushed it out. Magic burst along his bones, through his hands, and into the skeleton. Matthis collapsed.

He woke by vomiting again. But he hadn't needed food for days, so he heaved and heaved and heaved. He felt mud under his fingers. Rafe laid a hand on his back. He saw only stars. His eyes felt pushed outward. Then his cheek was in mud. He lay there and heaved several more times, but with less force. His muscles buzzed. With Rafe's help, he pulled himself to the gallows post and sat with his back leaned against it and his legs splayed. He panted, eyes closed.

"Did ..." Matthis said between breaths, "did it ... work?" Bright stars blocked his vision.

"The skeleton is here." Rafe sounded calm. "This is what magic was like for me the first time." He paused. "I've never tried domination on undead before, though."

"How could ... anyone ... get used to this?"

"You already know the answer to that."

Eyes still closed, Matthis nodded. But the motion caused a fresh wave of nausea to lurch through his stomach. After a few minutes of deep breathing, Matthis opened his eyes.

The bottom half of the cage had transformed into thin green vines with tiny red thorns that poked in every direction. The white bones that were once Osric stood inside the tangle, arms to its sides. Its empty sockets stared in no particular direction. Rafe was kneeling in the mud next to Matthis, and his toe almost made contact with the skeletal foot. Matthis had seen it stuff bits of flesh between its ribs many times, with squirrel and rabbit meat, or strips of the dead wizard. A breathing person knelt next to it, and it did nothing. The thorny vine had gotten lodged into the skeleton's hip and pelvic bones. It did nothing to remove them. The alarm chains that had swung under the gibbet lay in a heap at its feet.

Thrushes chirped at each other in the trees. A raven's croak echoed from far away, high up the Blackvein mountains. A merry chickadee whistled nearby. Mud soaked Matthis' trousers and caked his entire right side.

"I can do the rest of them," said Rafe.

Matthis stared up at the other skeletons and remembered it all. A mob had almost killed him over these skeletons. Muriel, Mercy, the boy, and a hundred other people just like them. The countless hours, the restless nights, the nightmares, the stench, the blood. Osric's skeleton stood still in its tangle of vines. The black skeleton moaned.

"Don't take this from me," Matthis said.

Rafe studied Matthis for a long moment. His jaw tightened. He closed his eyes and swallowed. He stood, nodded, and extended his hand.

"All right, Matthis."

He took Rafe's hand and held it. A look passed between them. Their grip tightened, and Matthis pulled himself up. His stomach wobbled, and his legs shook. He leaned against the gallows and panted.

Matthis dragged one foot in front of the other. Rafe backed away and watched. Matthis rounded the vine gibbet. Osric's skeleton did not move as he passed. Matthis' knees buckled, but he caught himself. The next skeleton reached for him. He held its wrists with shaky hands. He tried to muster anger again. He expected his blood to writhe again. But one image floated in his mind, one where the skeleton did not fight anymore. A word jumped to his throat, but he swallowed it before it could slip out.

Please.

The skeleton stopped fighting. Just like with Aura in the glass house, something deep within him ripped away. His bones ached. When he opened his eyes, his knees had sunk into the mud and involuntary coughs tore his throat. Something smacked his back with a squelch, and when he opened his eyes again he saw the sky. He had fallen.

"Rafe," he croaked, "tell me it worked."

Rafe's face blocked half the sky. "Tell me what happened, Matthis."

"It felt different that time," said Matthis. "Not domination, more like ... persuasion."

"Well, stop it. It'll kill you one day."

Matthis sat up. The skeleton he had touched still sat in its intact gibbet. Rafe was within striking distance of it, but it did not try to harm him. Matthis exhaled.

He flexed his hands. The nausea of his first attempt had gone, replaced with an ache that reminded him of the fever he had two years ago.

The skeleton's chains rattled. Rafe and Matthis froze. The skeleton reached behind its head and pulled the pin that held the clasp around its neck. The clasp fell open and clanked against the bars. Matthis gaped at it. The skeleton reached through the bars and pulled the pin on the gibbet's hasp. Rafe tensed. The skeleton pried its rusty cage apart and pulled itself out. When its feet hit mud, it stood there. Its empty sockets didn't seem aimless. It tipped its head back and looked up at the sky. It lowered its skull and trained the sockets directly at Matthis. It didn't move.

Rafe and Matthis stared at it and panted. When his breath slowed, Matthis moved his head to the right, and then to the left. The skull followed his movement.

The black skeleton's ribs gave a low, wooden whistle in the wind. The sun touched the top of the gibbets. Lifted by the breeze, thorny vines picked up and landed in the ribs of the newly freed skeleton. Without moving its sockets away from Matthis, it picked the vine out and dropped it in one fluid motion.

"We should have done this at night," said Matthis.

His eyes wide, Rafe nodded.

--

Matthis collapsed to his knees. Blood beaded on the gibbet above him like sweat on the rusted iron. Two more skeletons to go. Hands on his knees, Matthis panted. The sun had reached the bottom of the gallows.

"You're doing a lot better," said Rafe. "Domination is coming a lot easier now."

Matthis spat in the mud. Osric's skeleton stood tangled in vines. The freed skeleton still stared at Matthis. Next to it, one of the gibbets had vanished out of existence when he dominated its occupant. Rafe said he thought the bars had transformed into wind or air. The next gibbet had crushed the skeleton's legs when it fell. The place in the beam where it had once hung now spewed slimy, dead leaves. They smelled like mold. The gibbet for the skeleton he had just dominated dripped congealed gobs of blood and rust with a ploink into the mud below.

When Matthis opened his eyes, faint black lines connected the center of his chest to the skull of the skeleton in the blood gibbet. More black lines connected him to the others. He turned and saw another that led to the black skeleton. The freed skeleton did not have a black line connected to it. It still stared at him.

"Oh, you can see the black lines now," said Rafe. "Good."

"You really have known all along, haven't you?"

The crushed bones of the skeleton in the fallen gibbet wormed in the mud. Rafe pulled the pins from the hasp. The skeleton inside made no move to pull itself out. Rafe unlocked the collar and pulled it out by the neck. It clattered to the ground. Its leg bones inched toward it. Rafe watched as the cracks on the bones sealed shut and the pieces welded back together. In seconds, the intact skeleton stood up and faced nowhere in particular.

"Domination didn't do that," said Rafe.

Matthis shook his head. "Burn them or crush them, it doesn't matter. They always come back." He paused. "But usually not that fast."

Rafe nodded. He placed a hand on the skeleton and shoved it. It took a step back and resumed its stance as though nothing had happened.

A rustle of leaves. Matthis and Rafe jumped. The skeletons did nothing. A deer looked up from the forest and froze. Rafe relaxed. The wind shifted. The deer bounded away and disappeared into the trees. Humming birds squeaked and chased each other. A mournful dove cooed. A large glob of blood and rust slopped into the mud.

Matthis stood. He held the wrists of one of the last skeletons. Matthis closed his eyes. He didn't like domination. He visualized the skeleton sitting calm in its gibbet. A feeling he hadn't noticed before buzzed in his chest. But thinking back, he remembered this sensation with Aura and the freed skeleton. Something in him resonated with the skeleton in his hands. Please.

The magic still ripped out of him. He still fell into the mud. He still coughed. But when he opened his eyes, the gibbet was still intact. He smiled.

Much like the first freed skeleton, this one reached behind its head and released its collar. When it pulled itself out of its cage, its sockets followed Matthis' movement. It stood in the mud. Nothing but its skull moved.

"Damn it, Matthis," growled Rafe. "It might not kill you this time. And maybe not next time, either. But this ... persuasion, it will kill you."

Matthis flexed his hands. The skin had turned gray up to his elbows. He wiped the mud onto his trousers. The mud left, but his skin remained gray. The color of stone, or old bones.

Several minutes later, all eight skeletons stood under the gallows. Matthis had dominated the last one. Its cage had puffed into red smoke that still hung in the air in the shape of a gibbet. 

Matthis and Rafe stood before the gallows, their arms folded. The two freed skeletons looked at Matthis. The black skeleton moaned. The others faced random directions. A puffy white cloud passed overhead. A stale wind swept the smell of mud and blood and smoke into their faces. A happy flock of thrushes twittered somewhere in the trees. Green vines whipped in the wind. The hole in the beam like a lanced boil had stopped squirting moldy leaves, but the stench still stung their eyes. The black wizard moaned.

Matthis stepped forward. The black lines that connected him to seven of the skeletons vibrated.

"Show me what you want," he said.

For several seconds, there was no sound at all. Then in a chorus of bone clacks, the skeletons all stepped forward.